<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-08-16T01:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-08-15T04:00:00-05:00" n="254" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d254">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/2004: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName> [<date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates" calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1937-08-16T02:30:00-04:00" notBefore="1937-08-15T17:00:00+08:00">undated</date>].<lb/>[Received August 16, 1937—2:30
                                a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The Commander-in-Chief of the Asiatic Fleet and I have considered it
                            necessary in the extreme emergency and without advance specific
                            authorization from Washington to direct the Dollar Steamship Company’s
                            general manager for the Far East to divert their ships from regular
                            schedules to evacuate American women and children from Shanghai to
                            Manila. I respectfully request that any necessary action be obtained
                            from Congress to support the emergency action we have taken. Details
                            will be communicated later.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>